                        <h4>Tour: Distinctively Stately Scotland</h4>
                        <p> <b>Activity Level</b> : 3</p><hr>
                        <p>A VIP exploration through the majesty of Scotland</p>
                        <p>This royal journey leads you through the majesty of Scotland with an extraordinary VIP exploration of Bowhill House and grounds, aboard Her Majesty&rsquo;s Royal Yacht Britannia in Edinburgh, a visit to the sublime seasonal Royal Botanic Garden Dawyck.</p><hr><h4>Hotels: Barony Castle Hotel</h4><p></p><p>This imposing 16th century Castle has evolved into a traditional welcoming Hotel, Conference & Wedding Venue, located just 35 minutes (17 miles) south of Edinburgh on the edge of the Scottish Borders.  The lovely town of Peebles, which sits on the banks of the celebrated River Tweed, is only a 10-minute drive away.</p><h4>Hotels: Peebles Hydro</h4><p><p>A beautiful early 20th Century hotel, surrounded by forest, Peebles Hydro offers us a comfortable traditional oasis for our stay. Features include genuine Scottish breakfasts, indoor pool and gym, high-speed Wi-Fi, spectacular views and Peeble&rsquo;s very own gin distillery.</p></p><p>A beautiful early 20th Century hotel, surrounded by forest, Peebles Hydro offers us a comfortable traditional oasis for our stay. Features include genuine Scottish breakfasts, indoor pool and gym, high-speed Wi-Fi, spectacular views and Peeble&rsquo;s very own gin distillery.</p><h4>Hotels: Angel Hotel Cardiff</h4><p><p>The Angel Hotel is a beautiful Victorian landmark right in the heart of Cardiff. Neatly positioned between the Principality Stadium and Cardiff Castle, it&rsquo;s the perfect location for city breaks in Cardiff and for exploring the beautiful countryside and beaches of South Wales. Find out about the city&#39;s history at The National Museum of Wales, admire the architecture of Llandaff Cathedral and enjoy shopping, dining and water sports at Cardiff Bay. With 102 modern, air conditioned bedrooms, restaurant and bar, the Angel Hotel Cardiff is the perfect place to stay when exploring this vibrant and historic city.</p></p><p>The Angel Hotel is a beautiful Victorian landmark right in the heart of Cardiff. Neatly positioned between the Principality Stadium and Cardiff Castle, it's the perfect location for city breaks in Cardiff and for exploring the beautiful countryside and beaches of South Wales. Find out about the city's history at The National Museum of Wales, admire the architecture of Llandaff Cathedral and enjoy shopping, dining and water sports at Cardiff Bay. With 102 modern, air conditioned bedrooms, restaurant and bar, the Angel Hotel Cardiff is the perfect place to stay when exploring this vibrant and historic city.</p><h4>Hotels: Mercure Bristol Brigstow Hotel</h4><p><p>Mercure Brigstow Hotel is located in the vibrant part of Bristol City Centre, just steps away from main venues, Saint Nicolas Market, The Old Vic, Cabot Circus and the Harbour. Indulge in great quality food during the day or relax in the evening with a craft beer or cocktail at the bar.</p></p><p>Mercure Brigstow Hotel is located in the vibrant part of Bristol City Centre, just steps away from main venues, Saint Nicolas Market, The Old Vic, Cabot Circus and the Harbour. Indulge in great quality food during the day or relax in the evening with a craft beer or cocktail at the bar.</p><h4>Experience: The Royal Yacht Britannia</h4><p><p>A floating palace, Britannia was launched from the John Brown &amp; Company shipyard in Clydebank, Scotland, on 16 April, 1953. For over 44 years the Royal Yacht served the Royal Family, travelling more than a million nautical miles to become one of the most famous ships in the world. To Her Majesty The Queen, Britannia provided the perfect Royal residence for glittering state visits, official receptions, Royal honeymoons and relaxing family holidays. For Great Britain, she was a majestic symbol of the Commonwealth and a proud ambassador generating billions of pounds in trade deals. For the Royal Family and 220 dedicated crew of Royal Yachtsmen, she was home. Today, Britannia is a five-star visitor attraction in Edinburgh.</p></p><p>A floating palace, launched from Clydebank on 16 April, 1953, serving the Royal Family for 44 years and travelling more than a million nautical miles, Britannia became one of the most famous ships in the world, boarded by some of the most influential people, including Sir Winston Churchill, Boris Yeltsin, Rajiv Gandhi and Nelson Mandela. The perfect Royal residence to host state visits, official receptions, honeymoons and relaxing family holidays, the ship remains a majestic symbol of the Commonwealth. Now a 5-star visitor attraction, your guided tour will walk you through the State Apartments, crew quarters, the gleaming engine room, the state Dining Room and the Sun Lounge. Last five images courtesy of VisitScotland/Kenny Lam.</p><h4>Experience: Dawyck Botanical Garden</h4><p><p>Dawyck Botanic Garden is a five star Garden renowned for its seasonal displays of snowdrops, bluebells, rhododendrons, azaleas, blue poppies and autumn colour. Located in the hills of the Scottish Borders, 65-acre Dawyck enjoys an almost continental climate comprising warm dry summers followed by cold, snowy winters. Plants from the mountainous regions of Europe, China, Nepal, Japan and North America thrive here. Dawyck has one of Scotland&rsquo;s finest tree collections including some of Britain&rsquo;s oldest and tallest trees, dating back to 1680. Look out for Douglas fir, European Silver fir and Giant Sierra redwoods.</p></p><p>Renowned for astounding seasonal displays, 5-star, 65-acre Dawyck Botanic Garden located in the hills of the Scottish Borders, where a continental climate of warm dry summers followed by cold, snowy winters encourages plants to thrive, plays host to flora from the mountainous regions of Europe, China, Nepal, Japan and North America as well as Scotland&rsquo;s finest tree collections, and Britain&rsquo;s oldest and tallest trees, dating to 1680.</p><h4>Experience: Bowhill House</h4><p></p><p>This majestic, enchanting country house estate and its grounds have been a rural oasis for more than 200 years. Bowhill enjoys a regal seat in the heart of Ettrick ancient hunting forest, blessed with an abundance of glorious scenery, woodland once covering the hills and valleys, this is one of the Scottish Borders&rsquo; hidden treasures. Enlightening house tours reveal a history full of art, treasures and stories of the wrestling of the &lsquo;buck from the ravine&rsquo; and the Buccleuch family, gifted the estate by King Robert the Bruce for their loyalty.</p></body>

